1
00:00:49,209 --> 00:00:51,606
<i>( orchestral music</i> <i>playing )</i>

2
00:01:58,408 --> 00:02:02,575
<i>At rare intervals</i>
<i>there appears among us</i>

3
00:02:02,576 --> 00:02:05,077
<i>A person</i> <i>whose virtues</i>

4
00:02:05,078 --> 00:02:07,370
<i>Are so</i> <i>manifest to all,</i>

5
00:02:07,371 --> 00:02:09,455
<i>Who has</i> <i>such a capacity</i>

6
00:02:09,456 --> 00:02:12,268
<i>For relating to every sort</i>
<i>of human being,</i>

7
00:02:12,269 --> 00:02:15,706
<i>Who so subordinates</i>
<i>his own ego drives</i>

8
00:02:15,707 --> 00:02:18,313
<i>To the concerns</i> <i>of others,</i>

9
00:02:18,314 --> 00:02:21,021
<i>Who lives his whole life</i>
<i>in such Harmony</i>

10
00:02:21,022 --> 00:02:23,836
<i>With the prevailing</i>
<i>standards of the community</i>

11
00:02:23,837 --> 00:02:26,025
<i>That he is revered</i> <i>and loved</i>

12
00:02:26,026 --> 00:02:29,880
<i>By everyone with whom</i>
<i>he comes in contact.</i>

13
00:02:29,881 --> 00:02:34,778
<i>Such a man</i>
<i>Dalton Trumbo was not.</i>

14
00:02:34,779 --> 00:02:36,864
<i>( crowd chuckles )</i>

15
00:02:51,245 --> 00:02:53,224
During the second world war

16
00:02:53,225 --> 00:02:56,976
277 members of the guild
entered the armed services

17
00:02:56,977 --> 00:02:59,061
To fight what was then called

18
00:02:59,062 --> 00:03:01,978
The war against fascism.

19
00:03:01,979 --> 00:03:05,938
Five of them did not come back.

20
00:03:05,939 --> 00:03:10,002
Within six years
43 of those who did return

21
00:03:10,003 --> 00:03:12,087
Were denounced
as un-American,

22
00:03:12,088 --> 00:03:14,484
Stripped of their
names and passports

23
00:03:14,485 --> 00:03:17,193
And blacklisted.

24
00:03:17,194 --> 00:03:20,320
I presume that over half
of our members

25
00:03:20,321 --> 00:03:22,612
Have no memory
of that blacklist

26
00:03:22,613 --> 00:03:25,115
Because they were children
when it began

27
00:03:25,116 --> 00:03:27,824
Or not yet born.

28
00:03:27,825 --> 00:03:31,055
To them I would say only this:

29
00:03:34,286 --> 00:03:36,786
That the blacklist

30
00:03:36,787 --> 00:03:39,079
Was a time of evil

31
00:03:39,080 --> 00:03:41,996
And that no one
on either side who survived it

32
00:03:41,997 --> 00:03:46,166
Came through untouched by evil.

33
00:03:46,167 --> 00:03:48,250
Caught in the situation
that had passed

34
00:03:48,251 --> 00:03:51,897
Beyond the control
of mere individuals,

35
00:03:51,899 --> 00:03:54,607
Each person reacted
as his nature,

36
00:03:54,608 --> 00:03:57,421
His needs, his convictions

37
00:03:57,422 --> 00:04:00,234
And his
particular circumstances

38
00:04:00,235 --> 00:04:02,736
Compelled him to.

39
00:04:02,737 --> 00:04:05,133
There was bad Faith and good,

40
00:04:05,134 --> 00:04:08,050
Honesty and dishonesty

41
00:04:08,051 --> 00:04:10,239
Courage and cowardice,

42
00:04:10,240 --> 00:04:12,427
Selflessness and opportunism,

43
00:04:12,428 --> 00:04:15,450
Wisdom and stupidity,
good and bad

44
00:04:15,451 --> 00:04:17,430
On both sides.

45
00:04:17,431 --> 00:04:20,348
And almost every
individual involved,

46
00:04:20,349 --> 00:04:22,954
No matter where he stood,

47
00:04:22,955 --> 00:04:25,350
Combined some or all

48
00:04:25,351 --> 00:04:27,435
Of these antithetical qualities

49
00:04:27,436 --> 00:04:31,811
In his own person,
in his own acts.

50
00:04:31,812 --> 00:04:34,835
Interviewer:
<i>Dalton Trumbo... he's a very</i>
<i>distinguished film writer.</i>

51
00:04:34,731 --> 00:04:37,127
<i>He's won academy awards.</i>
<i>He's a letter writer too.</i>

52
00:04:37,128 --> 00:04:39,733
<i>And they're obstreperous.</i>
<i>They're funny.</i>

53
00:04:39,629 --> 00:04:41,818
- <i>They're eloquent.</i>
- Trumbo: <i>Well, I suppose so.</i>

54
00:04:41,713 --> 00:04:43,797
Interviewer:
<i>And so these letters</i>
<i>that you wrote</i>

55
00:04:43,798 --> 00:04:47,028
<i>Dealing with yourself,</i>
<i>your independence,</i>
<i>your stubbornness...</i>

56
00:04:47,029 --> 00:04:49,737
Trumbo:
<i>Words are lost on the air...</i>
<i>the spoken word.</i>

57
00:04:49,738 --> 00:04:53,072
<i>You never know</i>
<i>really what you said</i>
<i>in the last conversation,</i>

58
00:04:53,073 --> 00:04:55,156
<i>Whereas if you sit down</i>
<i>and write</i>

59
00:04:55,157 --> 00:04:57,866
<i>A concise definition</i>
<i>of your problem,</i>

60
00:04:57,762 --> 00:04:59,847
<i>It commands</i>
<i>the man's attention.</i>

61
00:04:59,742 --> 00:05:02,347
Interviewer:
<i>So your letters</i>
<i>to all variety of people,</i>

62
00:05:02,348 --> 00:05:04,327
<i>Friends and enemies</i>

63
00:05:04,328 --> 00:05:07,870
<i>In 1942 to 1962,</i>

64
00:05:07,871 --> 00:05:10,684
<i>You almost tell us</i>
<i>the story of our country</i>

65
00:05:10,685 --> 00:05:13,810
<i>Through the eyes</i>
<i>of this very stubborn man</i>
<i>Dalton Trumbo.</i>

66
00:05:13,811 --> 00:05:16,729
Trumbo:
<i>It was very lively</i>
<i>two decades...</i>

67
00:05:16,730 --> 00:05:19,334
<i>Very lively.</i>
<i>One was rarely bored.</i>

68
00:05:19,335 --> 00:05:21,419
Interviewer:
<i>All your warts</i>
<i>are here too,</i>

69
00:05:21,314 --> 00:05:24,024
<i>'cause you're pretty...</i>
<i>you're rough, you know,</i>
<i>at times.</i>

70
00:05:24,026 --> 00:05:27,462
"warty warty"...
I prefer the word
"abrasive."

71
00:05:27,463 --> 00:05:29,548
- <i>Abrasive.</i>
- <i>But "warty"</i>
<i>is just as good.</i>

72
00:05:29,444 --> 00:05:31,528
Helen Manfull:
<i>I discovered</i>
<i>the correspondence</i>

73
00:05:31,529 --> 00:05:33,507
<i>As a processor</i>

74
00:05:33,508 --> 00:05:36,217
<i>At the Wisconsin center</i>
<i>for theater research.</i>

75
00:05:36,218 --> 00:05:38,614
<i>And they were collecting</i>
<i>the materials</i>

76
00:05:38,615 --> 00:05:41,427
Of the Hollywood 10.

77
00:05:41,428 --> 00:05:44,033
One of the collections
that I got to process

78
00:05:44,034 --> 00:05:46,221
Was the collection
of Dalton Trumbo...

79
00:05:46,222 --> 00:05:48,931
Box upon box upon box.

80
00:05:48,932 --> 00:05:53,308
It's the story
of an absolutely devoted

81
00:05:53,309 --> 00:05:55,809
And passionate family man,

82
00:05:55,810 --> 00:05:58,518
<i>Trumbo's love</i> <i>of his wife Cleo,</i>

83
00:05:58,519 --> 00:06:00,500
<i>Of their</i> <i>three children.</i>

84
00:06:00,501 --> 00:06:03,833
<i>It's the story</i> <i>of the blacklist</i>

85
00:06:03,834 --> 00:06:05,919
<i>And what it did</i> <i>to people.</i>

86
00:06:05,920 --> 00:06:08,420
<i>It also</i> <i>made me aware</i>

87
00:06:08,421 --> 00:06:10,294
Of what it means

88
00:06:10,295 --> 00:06:12,692
To be true to your principles

89
00:06:12,693 --> 00:06:15,090
And to be willing
to stand up for what
you believe

90
00:06:15,091 --> 00:06:17,382
No matter what
the consequences are.

91
00:06:17,383 --> 00:06:19,257
Trumbo's this person

92
00:06:19,258 --> 00:06:21,862
With an unbelievably strong
sense of Justice, you know,

93
00:06:21,863 --> 00:06:24,364
And what's right.

94
00:06:24,365 --> 00:06:26,449
And the letters for him

95
00:06:26,450 --> 00:06:28,845
Are his, as it were, forum

96
00:06:28,846 --> 00:06:31,555
To express that.

97
00:06:31,556 --> 00:06:33,744
He was so opinionated
and so passionate

98
00:06:33,745 --> 00:06:36,974
And so inventive
and sharp and funny

99
00:06:36,975 --> 00:06:41,663
That you just didn't
win an argument with him.

100
00:06:41,664 --> 00:06:45,416
He would be one of our heroes

101
00:06:45,417 --> 00:06:48,229
Because he was an iconoclast.

102
00:06:48,230 --> 00:06:51,564
He just plain was
a little grandiose, I think.

103
00:06:51,565 --> 00:06:53,545
He wasn't confrontational
in the sense

104
00:06:53,546 --> 00:06:55,420
He went out
looking for trouble.

105
00:06:55,421 --> 00:06:56,984
It seemed to come to him.

106
00:06:56,985 --> 00:06:59,171
Dalton was a contrarian,
you know.

107
00:06:59,172 --> 00:07:01,152
He had fights.

108
00:07:01,153 --> 00:07:05,111
I'm just glad he never
had a fight with me.

109
00:07:05,112 --> 00:07:09,176
Trumbo:
<i>I think of myself</i>
<i>as an extremely peaceable man.</i>

110
00:07:09,177 --> 00:07:13,136
<i>God knows I never wanted</i>
<i>to fight in my life,</i>

111
00:07:13,137 --> 00:07:17,307
<i>But sometimes I think</i>
<i>they're forced upon</i>
<i>a peaceful man.</i>

112
00:07:25,643 --> 00:07:28,665
My father
always had an ambition
to become a writer.

113
00:07:28,666 --> 00:07:30,644
And once he gets started,

114
00:07:30,645 --> 00:07:32,730
Publishing his first book

115
00:07:32,731 --> 00:07:35,335
In 1933 or 1934,

116
00:07:35,336 --> 00:07:39,399
By 1940 he's published
three novels,

117
00:07:39,400 --> 00:07:41,484
<i>Won a national</i> <i>book award</i>

118
00:07:41,485 --> 00:07:44,922
And written
about 20 screenplays.

119
00:07:44,923 --> 00:07:47,008
And he's been nominated
for an Oscar also.

120
00:07:47,009 --> 00:07:50,966
So he has, you know,
sort of a brilliant

121
00:07:50,967 --> 00:07:52,427
Seven-years beginning.

122
00:07:52,428 --> 00:07:54,822
Up to about 1945

123
00:07:54,823 --> 00:07:58,053
<i>He was the highest-paid</i>
<i>screenwriter in Hollywood.</i>

124
00:07:58,054 --> 00:08:02,221
<i>He had a contract</i>
<i>without a morality clause.</i>

125
00:08:02,222 --> 00:08:05,036
He was very very successful.

126
00:08:05,037 --> 00:08:07,641
Everybody wanted

127
00:08:07,642 --> 00:08:10,559
To use the name
of Dalton Trumbo.

128
00:08:10,560 --> 00:08:14,623
He probably was the best writer

129
00:08:14,624 --> 00:08:16,916
At that time.

130
00:08:16,917 --> 00:08:19,209
And then it all fell apart.

131
00:08:19,210 --> 00:08:22,024
Newsreel announcer:
<i>In Washington, the committee</i>
<i>on un-American activities</i>

132
00:08:22,025 --> 00:08:24,941
<i>Opens new hearings</i>
<i>in a jam-packed caucus room.</i>

133
00:08:24,942 --> 00:08:27,025
<i>Here charges</i> <i>of red influence</i>

134
00:08:27,026 --> 00:08:29,527
<i>Directed against</i>
<i>the motion picture industry</i>
<i>are aired.</i>

135
00:08:29,528 --> 00:08:31,923
This committee
under its mandate

136
00:08:31,924 --> 00:08:34,007
From the house
of representatives

137
00:08:34,008 --> 00:08:36,613
Has the responsibility
of exposing

138
00:08:36,614 --> 00:08:39,218
And spotlighting
subversive elements

139
00:08:39,219 --> 00:08:41,095
Wherever they may exist.

140
00:08:41,096 --> 00:08:44,637
McCarthy was seeing communists

141
00:08:44,638 --> 00:08:47,764
In congress,

142
00:08:47,765 --> 00:08:50,890
In the white house,
in the army,

143
00:08:50,891 --> 00:08:54,851
And especially in
the movie industry,

144
00:08:54,852 --> 00:08:59,227
And especially
with the writers.

145
00:08:59,228 --> 00:09:02,666
Man:
<i>What about Mr. Dalton Trumbo?</i>
<i>Do you know Mr. Dalton Trumbo?</i>

146
00:09:02,667 --> 00:09:04,752
Yes, I know
Mr. Trumbo.

147
00:09:04,753 --> 00:09:07,461
<i>Mr. Trumbo was the editor</i>
<i>of the official</i>

148
00:09:07,462 --> 00:09:09,441
- <i>Publication of the guild,</i>
<i>was he not?</i>
- Yes, that's true.

149
00:09:09,442 --> 00:09:12,150
Yes, at one time
Dalton Trumbo was editor
of "the screenwriter,"

150
00:09:12,151 --> 00:09:14,131
The monthly publication of
the screenwriters' guild.

151
00:09:14,027 --> 00:09:16,111
<i>Do you think</i>
<i>that Dalton Trumbo</i>
<i>was a communist?</i>

152
00:09:16,112 --> 00:09:18,507
Well, certainly I have
no information on that

153
00:09:18,508 --> 00:09:20,593
Beyond what I've heard
here this week.

154
00:09:20,594 --> 00:09:23,198
People joined
the communist party
because it was doing something.

155
00:09:23,093 --> 00:09:25,387
It was an effective instrument.
It was doing things

156
00:09:25,388 --> 00:09:27,782
That they felt should be done.

157
00:09:27,783 --> 00:09:31,221
It was opposing
the rise of fascism

158
00:09:31,223 --> 00:09:33,202
All through Europe.

159
00:09:33,203 --> 00:09:36,328
It was helping those
who were refugees.

160
00:09:36,329 --> 00:09:37,996
I remember as a kid

161
00:09:37,997 --> 00:09:40,393
The conversations would be
about the soviet union.

162
00:09:40,289 --> 00:09:41,644
<i>This was</i> <i>the depression.</i>

163
00:09:41,645 --> 00:09:43,936
<i>The country was</i>
<i>in a depression.</i>

164
00:09:43,937 --> 00:09:47,063
Socialism, communism
seemed like somewhat
of a solution

165
00:09:47,064 --> 00:09:49,355
To everybody being out of work.

166
00:09:49,356 --> 00:09:52,898
Russia had been our allies
through the early 1940s.

167
00:09:52,899 --> 00:09:55,503
<i>And then all of a sudden</i>
<i>they became our enemy.</i>

168
00:09:55,505 --> 00:09:57,485
It is my duty
to place before you

169
00:09:57,486 --> 00:09:59,151
Certain facts

170
00:09:59,152 --> 00:10:01,548
About the present
position in Europe.

171
00:10:01,549 --> 00:10:05,091
An iron curtain has
descended across the continent.

172
00:10:05,092 --> 00:10:07,385
Newsreel announcer:
<i>A growing struggle</i>
<i>between two great powers</i>

173
00:10:07,386 --> 00:10:09,574
<i>To shape</i> <i>the postwar world.</i>

174
00:10:09,470 --> 00:10:11,241
<i>On orders</i> <i>from the Kremlin</i>

175
00:10:11,136 --> 00:10:13,012
<i>Russia had launched</i>
<i>one of history's</i>

176
00:10:13,014 --> 00:10:15,618
<i>Most drastic political,</i>
<i>moral and economic wars...</i>

177
00:10:15,619 --> 00:10:17,284
<i>A cold war.</i>

178
00:10:17,285 --> 00:10:19,370
Trumbo:
<i>We were ready for war</i>

179
00:10:19,371 --> 00:10:23,224
<i>And felt it was coming.</i>
<i>And people didn't want it,</i>

180
00:10:23,225 --> 00:10:25,413
<i>But they were frightened.</i>

181
00:10:25,414 --> 00:10:28,332
<i>And with the public</i>
<i>that frightened</i>

182
00:10:28,333 --> 00:10:31,145
One can understand

183
00:10:31,146 --> 00:10:33,542
How things like this
could happen.

184
00:10:33,543 --> 00:10:35,315
If you want to scare a country,

185
00:10:35,419 --> 00:10:38,544
You go after its royalty.
And Hollywood was our royalty.

186
00:10:38,545 --> 00:10:40,838
<i>And they had two rounds</i>
<i>of witnesses.</i>

187
00:10:40,839 --> 00:10:42,922
<i>And the first round</i> <i>were mostly</i>

188
00:10:42,923 --> 00:10:45,632
<i>Either friendly witnesses</i>
<i>or executives.</i>

189
00:10:45,633 --> 00:10:48,445
<i>The committee wanted</i>
<i>to bask in the publicity glow</i>

190
00:10:48,446 --> 00:10:52,614
And fame of the stars
and of Hollywood.

191
00:10:52,615 --> 00:10:55,635
This is a foul philosophy...
this communistic thing.

192
00:10:55,636 --> 00:10:58,345
I would move
to the state of Texas
if it ever came here

193
00:10:58,346 --> 00:11:00,743
Because I think that Texans
would kill them on sight.

194
00:11:00,744 --> 00:11:02,201
( crowd laughs )

195
00:11:02,202 --> 00:11:05,224
If I had my way about it
they'd all be sent back

196
00:11:05,225 --> 00:11:07,828
To Russia or some other
unpleasant place.

197
00:11:07,829 --> 00:11:10,538
<i>( applause,</i> <i>gavel pounds )</i>

198
00:11:10,539 --> 00:11:13,352
I don't believe
it's a political party.

199
00:11:13,353 --> 00:11:15,333
I believe
it's an un-American thing.

200
00:11:15,334 --> 00:11:19,083
And I feel that they really
ought to be smoked out

201
00:11:19,085 --> 00:11:21,065
And shown up for what they are

202
00:11:21,066 --> 00:11:23,774
So that all the good
free causes in this country,

203
00:11:23,775 --> 00:11:26,380
All the liberalisms
that really are American

204
00:11:26,381 --> 00:11:29,090
Can go out without
the stain of communism.

205
00:11:29,091 --> 00:11:33,465
And then they called...
I believe it was 19 people.

206
00:11:33,467 --> 00:11:36,071
And eventually

207
00:11:36,072 --> 00:11:38,572
It boiled down
to the Hollywood 10.

208
00:11:38,573 --> 00:11:40,553
Trumbo:
<i>Well, we were called</i>
<i>originally</i>

209
00:11:40,554 --> 00:11:42,845
<i>"the unfriendly 10."</i>

210
00:11:42,846 --> 00:11:44,305
<i>And I like that</i> <i>much better.</i>

211
00:11:44,306 --> 00:11:45,868
Interviewer:
<i>Unfriendly to what?</i>

212
00:11:45,764 --> 00:11:47,849
Trumbo:
<i>To that committee</i>
<i>and to anybody else</i>

213
00:11:47,850 --> 00:11:49,931
<i>Who interfered...</i>

214
00:11:49,932 --> 00:11:53,267
<i>Who tried to force</i>
<i>a compulsory confession</i>

215
00:11:53,268 --> 00:11:56,081
<i>Of beliefs, Faith,</i>
<i>anything else.</i>

216
00:12:04,106 --> 00:12:06,190
An official purpose of theirs

217
00:12:06,191 --> 00:12:08,898
Was to discover
communist propaganda

218
00:12:08,899 --> 00:12:11,400
In the films that
these folks had written.

219
00:12:11,401 --> 00:12:13,277
It's a fallacy to think
that they got

220
00:12:13,278 --> 00:12:16,506
Overtly leftist themes
into films,

221
00:12:16,507 --> 00:12:19,008
But as many scholars before me

222
00:12:19,009 --> 00:12:21,196
Have noted quite elegantly,

223
00:12:21,197 --> 00:12:23,176
What they did is

224
00:12:23,177 --> 00:12:26,095
They were able to shift subtly

225
00:12:26,096 --> 00:12:28,282
Some of the archetypes

226
00:12:28,283 --> 00:12:31,097
That were really important
in American films
of that era.

227
00:12:31,098 --> 00:12:33,390
You wrote from a particular
point of view, you know.

228
